File: e2e/hot-reload-dynamic.e2e.ts, around lines 533-543

Current code:
```typescript
const deadline = Date.now() + 20_000;
while (Date.now() < deadline) {
  const injected = await page.evaluate(() => {
    const ot = (globalThis as Record<string, unknown>).__openTabs as
      | { adapters?: Record<string, unknown> }
      | undefined;
    return ot?.adapters?.['e2e-test'] !== undefined;
  });
  if (injected) break;
  await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 500));
}
```

Problem: If the deadline passes without adapter injection, execution falls through silently. The test continues to line 546 (waitForToolResult) which eventually fails with a confusing timeout error that doesn't mention adapter injection.

Fix: Add a throw after the while loop if the adapter was never injected:
```typescript
const deadline = Date.now() + 20_000;
let injected = false;
while (Date.now() < deadline) {
  injected = await page.evaluate(() => {
    const ot = (globalThis as Record<string, unknown>).__openTabs as
      | { adapters?: Record<string, unknown> }
      | undefined;
    return ot?.adapters?.['e2e-test'] !== undefined;
  });
  if (injected) break;
  await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 500));
}
if (!injected) {
  throw new Error('e2e-test adapter was not injected within 20s');
}
```

Alternatively, use the existing `waitFor` helper from helpers.ts which handles this correctly:
```typescript
await waitFor(
  async () => {
    return page.evaluate(() => {
      const ot = (globalThis as Record<string, unknown>).__openTabs as
        | { adapters?: Record<string, unknown> }
        | undefined;
      return ot?.adapters?.['e2e-test'] !== undefined;
    });
  },
  20_000,
  500,
  'e2e-test adapter to be injected into tab',
);
```

File: e2e/tab-state-sync.e2e.ts, around line 316

Current code:
```typescript
// 4. Wait a moment for the extension to detect the disconnection.
// The offscreen document's pong timeout is 5s, so we wait enough time
// for the WebSocket close to be detected.
await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 8_000));
```

The test already imports waitForExtensionDisconnected from helpers.ts (check the imports at the top of the file). This helper polls the server health endpoint until extensionConnected becomes false, with proper timeout and error messaging.

Replace with:
```typescript
// Wait for the extension to detect the disconnection.
// The offscreen document's pong timeout is 5s, plus buffer for detection.
await waitForExtensionDisconnected(server1, 15_000);
```

Note: Check the imports — if waitForExtensionDisconnected is not imported, add it to the import from './helpers.js'. The function signature is: waitForExtensionDisconnected(server: McpServer, timeoutMs?: number): Promise<void>

Also note: this test manages its own server lifecycle (server1, server2), not using fixtures. The server1 variable is what should be passed to waitForExtensionDisconnected since it has just been killed on line 311.

File: e2e/iife-injection.e2e.ts

Two tests in the 'IIFE injection — overlapping URL patterns' describe block create tmpDirs for extra plugins but only clean them up at the end of the test body (happy path). If an assertion or wait fails mid-test, the tmpDir leaks.

Test 1: 'two plugins with overlapping URL patterns both inject adapters' (around lines 419-482)
- tmpDir created at ~line 419 with fs.mkdtempSync
- tmpDir cleaned up at ~line 482 with fs.rmSync
- No try/finally wrapping the assertions

Test 2: 'tool dispatch works with overlapping URL patterns...' (around lines 500-567)
- tmpDir created at ~line 500 with fs.mkdtempSync
- tmpDir cleaned up at ~line 566 with fs.rmSync
- No try/finally wrapping the assertions

These are fixture-based tests (using fixtureTest), so the MCP server/extension/browser are cleaned up by fixtures. Only the tmpDir needs manual cleanup.

Fix: Wrap the test body after tmpDir creation in a try/finally:
```typescript
const tmpDir = fs.mkdtempSync(...);
try {
  // ... existing test body ...
} finally {
  fs.rmSync(tmpDir, { recursive: true, force: true });
}
```

Remove the existing fs.rmSync at the end of the test body since it's now in the finally block.

Two files have the same flaky pattern: fire a slow tool call, sleep 500ms, then do something (modify IIFE / replace WebSocket) while the call is in-flight. The 500ms sleep is a guess that may be too short under heavy CI load.

File 1: e2e/iife-injection.e2e.ts, around line 597
The test fires a slow tool call (~10s duration) and then modifies the IIFE file. The 500ms sleep is meant to ensure the slow call has reached the test server before the IIFE modification.

File 2: e2e/dispatch-resilience.e2e.ts, around line 518
The test fires a tool call and then replaces the extension's WebSocket. The 500ms sleep is meant to ensure the tool dispatch message was sent before the WebSocket is replaced.

Fix approach: The test server has a /control/invocations endpoint (see test-server.ts). Poll it using waitFor until the in-flight request appears:

```typescript
// Instead of: await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 500));
await waitFor(
  async () => {
    const invocations = await testServer.invocations();
    return invocations.some(i => i.path === '/api/slow');
  },
  10_000,
  200,
  'slow tool call to reach test server',
);
```

For dispatch-resilience.e2e.ts, check what API endpoint the in-flight tool call hits (it may be /api/echo or /api/slow depending on the test). Look at the tool being called and what endpoint it maps to.

Note: The slow tool call in iife-injection.e2e.ts uses the test server's /api/slow endpoint which takes ~10s. The invocations endpoint records all requests, so polling for /api/slow in the invocations list proves the request has arrived.

For dispatch-resilience.e2e.ts, verify the exact endpoint by reading the test at ~line 510 to see which tool is called. The pattern may use e2e-test_slow_tool or similar. The invocations() helper returns all recorded API calls.

Import waitFor from helpers.ts if not already imported in the affected files.
